title: For Sale:  Vintage Daisy SoftAir Tec-9 Replica Airsoft Gun, New Old Stock!!
postcontent:
For sale is a New Old Stock, Daisy Model 12 SoftAir gun, a replica of the Tec-9 handgun.

These were the first airsoft guns brought into the US and were made back in 1987-88 and only sold for 1 year until they were pulled from stores because of how much they resemble the real guns (kids where being held at gunpoint by police officers because of the realism of these replicas). Since this all airsoft guns now require permenant orange tips on the barrel ends or must be a non-gun color, to distinguish "toys" from real firearms.

These airsoft guns fire standard airsoft bb's HOWEVER the bb's are loaded into lifesize 9mm shells and are loaded into an actual magazine! You pump the gun, the bb shoots out and the shell ejects, just like a real gun.
This is a very high quality item, metal and plastic parts and originally sold for $70 back in the 80's!

The gun for sale is as mint as you are going to ever find one. This is New Old Stock, never removed from the box, still has the zip-tie holding the bolt forward, all the shells, targets, manual, sling, bb's, and everything it originally came with. 99% condition, the other 1% is light shelf wear on the box, which will happen to any item sitting on a store shelf.

Asking $135 cash. I had 3 of these, this is my last one!
Will ship for $10.

title: For Trade:  Converted Saiga 5.56/.223 trade for 7.62x39 AK
postcontent: I have a properly converted Saiga .223/5.56 which has been refinished in KG GunKote (flat black). The gun is very accurate for an AK pattern rifle, and it also features a chrome lined barrrel (16"). Besides the bolt assembly, all the internals have been replaced with Tapco parts in order to remain 922r compliant. The gun features a G2 trigger group (polished by Dinzag Arms, the trigger pull is significantly better than standard AK's). I put a Tapco retaining plate in the gun, and the trigger guard is from Dinzag Arms. All of the holes which remained from conversion are filled with nylon plugs, also from Dinzag. The rear stock and pistol grip are by Tapco, and the gun features a tactical fore end (rail system) which also will retain a solid zero if optics are installed. The gun has had a Dinzag bullet guide installed...for those unfamiliar with Saiga rifles this is a feature which is necessary for high capacity magazines. I'm including the factory Saiga magazine with the gun, but aftermarket high capacity mags can be used with this rifle (I can't guarantee a drop in fit with every mag, some may need minor fitting to properly seat). The dust cover has been replaced by a mil spec ribbed version.
